A point (which we represent by a dot in drawings) is zero-
dimensional, since you don't have to specify any measurements to 
determine where you are in the point.

A line is one-dimensional, since it takes only one number to know 
where you are.

See these pages:

  Two Interpretations of Dimensionality in Geometric Figures
  http://mathforum.org/library/drmath/view/64865.html

  One Dimension
  http://mathforum.org/library/drmath/view/62847.html

If you have any further questions, feel free to write back.


- Doctor Peterson, The Math Forum
